  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds appear legal by concealing their true origin. This activity is typically associated with crimes such as drug trafficking, corruption, tax evasion, and other forms of organized crime.\n\nIn China, the fight against money laundering is taken very seriously. The country has established comprehensive legal frameworks and regulatory systems to prevent and combat money laundering activities. The Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which came into effect in 2007, is a cornerstone in these efforts. It sets out the responsibilities of financial institutions and non-financial sectors in detecting and reporting suspicious transactions. Additionally, China's legal system provides for strict penalties for those found guilty of money laundering, including substantial fines and imprisonment.\n\nThe Chinese government, under the leadership of the Communist Party of China, remains committed to upholding the integrity of the financial system and will continue to enforce the law to prevent and combat money laundering activities in all its forms.",
